1. How networking works in KVM (two main models)
✅ A. Default network (NAT + DHCP)

This is what you’re now using:

--network network=default
🔧 Architecture
VM (192.168.122.x)
     ↓
virbr0 (libvirt bridge on host)
     ↓ NAT (iptables/masquerade)
Host NIC (eth0)
     ↓
External network / Internet
🔍 Components
virbr0 → virtual bridge created by libvirt
dnsmasq → provides DHCP + DNS
IP range → usually 192.168.122.0/24
📡 DHCP flow
VM boots → sends DHCP request
dnsmasq (on host) replies
VM gets IP like 192.168.122.10
👍 Pros
Works everywhere (including GCP ✔️)
Zero configuration
Safe isolation
👎 Cons
VM not directly reachable from outside
NAT involved (not real network presence)
✅ B. Bridge network (real LAN IP)
--network bridge=br0
🔧 Architecture
VM (192.168.1.x)
     ↓
br0 (Linux bridge)
     ↓
eth0 (physical NIC)
     ↓
Same LAN as host
📡 DHCP flow
VM sends DHCP request
Your real router/DHCP server responds
VM gets IP like 192.168.1.50
👍 Pros
VM acts like real machine on network
Direct SSH, ping, etc.
Required for production clusters
👎 Cons
Needs L2 support (not available in GCP ❌)
More setup
⚖️ Which is better?
Use case	Best option
GCP / Cloud VM	✅ Default (NAT)
Local lab (laptop/server)	Bridge
Production / real infra	Bridge
Learning KVM basics	Default

👉 For YOU (GCP):
Default network is the correct and only practical choice

🚀 2. Live migration support

Now the important part 👇

❓ Can you do live migration with default NAT network?

👉 Technically: YES
👉 Practically: LIMITED / NOT recommended

🧠 Why?
With default network:
Each host has its own:
virbr0
DHCP (dnsmasq)
VM IP = not portable across hosts

👉 After migration:

VM may get new IP
Connectivity may break
❌ Problems in real scenarios
SSH sessions break
Cluster communication breaks
Services become unreachable
✅ With bridge network (ideal for migration)
VM keeps same IP (from real network)
No NAT dependency
Seamless migration

👉 That’s why:
➡️ Bridge networking is standard for live migration setups

🔥 Important for your GCP case

Since:

GCP blocks L2 / bridge
You must use NAT

👉 Live migration:

Possible only in lab/testing sense
Not production-grade
💡 Workarounds (if you want to simulate migration)
Option 1: Static IP inside NAT

Assign fixed IP:

192.168.122.100

But still:

Only valid per host
Option 2: Use same libvirt network config on all hosts
Same subnet
Same DHCP range

Still not perfect, but helps in labs.

Option 3 (Advanced / Real-world approach)

Use overlay networking:

VXLAN
Kubernetes CNI
Software-defined networking

(Advanced—can guide later)

🧠 Final recommendation for you
Right now:

✔ Use network=default
✔ Use DHCP
✔ Focus on:

KVM basics
Multi-node lab
SSH connectivity
Later (when moving to real infra):

Switch to:
✔ Bridge networking
✔ Static IP or external DHCP
✔ Proper migration setup

🚀 Simple summary
Feature	Default (NAT)	Bridge
DHCP	Host (dnsmasq)	External
Internet	NAT	Direct
Reachability	Limited	Full
GCP support	✅	❌
Live migration	⚠️ Limited	✅ Best

